<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-08-1032 </DOCNO><TEXT>Arguments for considering a select group of goods as merit goods are re-examined,and the claim that these should be provided directly by special benefitsrather than through general income supports is considered. Energy consumptioncharacteristics and differences in consumption at different income levelsand for different household types are discussed, and it is demonstratedthat energy falls into the merit good category. Current treatment ofenergy in the tax and benefit systems, and codes of conduct in terminatingsupply are reviewed. A number of alternative means of supplying energyto the poor are presented. Conclusions reached include the desirabilityof a specific energy supplement which will be of most benefit to thepoor and can be designed to meet market failures.</TEXT></DOC>